[2] UK (Merseyside)
Date: Mon 9 May 2011
Source: Liverpool Daily Post [edited]
http://www.liverpooldailypost.co.uk/liverpool-news/regional-news/2011/05/09/wirral-patient-seriously-ill-in-hospital-after-measles-outbreak-92534-28657106/


The Health Protection Agency (HPA) last night warned people to ensure
their children were immunised after several people were struck down
with the viral disease in Wirral.

There have been 2 confirmed cases, both children, and an undisclosed
number of suspected cases in both children and adults. One of these
patients is in hospital. None of those affected was fully immunised.

Dr Sam Ghebrehewet, Director of the HPA's Cheshire and Merseyside
Health Protection Unit, said: "These cases in Wirral show just how
important it is for parents to ensure that their children are given 2
doses of MMR [measles mumps and rubella] vaccine. We are also
reminding teenagers and young adults who haven't previously been
vaccinated that it is not too late for them. They should seek advice
from their family doctors. MMR [vaccine] is a safe and effective. Two
doses give full immunity against measles, mumps and rubella, diseases
that can have serious side effects. On very rare occasions people die
from measles."

The HPA also warned about a outbreak of measles across Europe,
particularly in France. The agency has strongly advised parents who
may be taking children on a continental holiday this summer [2011] to
ensure that they are fully protected by 2 doses of MMR vaccine. Doses
of MMR vaccine are normally given at 13 months and between the ages of
3 and 4 years, just before the child goes to school. However, children
of any age, including teenagers and young adults, can still be
vaccinated if they missed out on immunisation when they were younger.

Two doses of MMR vaccine are needed for complete protection. Measles
is an infectious viral illness that is spread when infected people
cough or sneeze. The most common symptoms are fever, coughs, sore eyes
and a rash that develops 3 to 4 days after the onset of illness,
starting with the face and head and spreading down the body. Parents
should not take children with suspected measles symptoms to their GP
surgery or local hospital's A&E unit, where they might risk passing on
the infection to other vulnerable children. Information on measles is
also available at http://www.immunisation.nhs.uk.

