[4] France (Nimes)
Date: Fri 13 May 2011
Source: Midi Libre [in French, trans. abbreviated & edited]
http://www.midilibre.fr/2011/05/12/l-epidemie-de-rougeole-frappe-fort-a-nimes,318050.php


Measles is a disease usually mild but distressing in children,
sometimes with serious consequences requiring hospitalization. There
has been a sharp upsurge in France and in the region in recent months.
This has been a consequence of insufficient vaccine coverage in the
local population, according to the Regional Health Agency (LRA).

A young mother with measles-affected children, interviewed by Midi
Libre, said she had not deemed it necessary to have her children
vaccinated in the conviction that vaccination weakens the immune
system. "But, I can tell you that I have completely changed my mind. I
regret not having them vaccinated," she said.

The youngest of her daughters is enrolled in a school with several
hundred pupils where many of the parents are opposed to vaccination
and which has been badly affected by the outbreak. Indeed, more than
half the pupils at this school have been affected. In the opinion of a
local GP in Nimes, this is no surprise, since in 90 percent of cases,
the children suffering from measles had not been vaccinated. The
remaining 10 percent of affected children are those who have not
received the 2nd dose of vaccine. The MMR (measles, mumps, rubella)
vaccine recommended by health authorities should be delivered in 2
doses, the 1st at one year of age and the 2nd between 3 and 6 years of
age.

The GP said that in recent weeks he has seen a dozen cases in his
office, "something I have not seen in the past 20 years. It's the same
with my colleagues, and it is continuing," he added. "This confirms
the magnitude of the current epidemic. The Regional Health Agency has
stated that for a population to be protected, there must be 95 percent
immunization coverage. But in the [Languedoc-Roussilon] region at
present, only 80 to 85 percent (and in some areas only 50 percent) of
the population have been vaccinated."

