[5] France (Reunion)
Date: Thu 12 May 2011
Source: Journal de l'ile [in French, trans. & edited]
http://www.clicanoo.re/11-actualites/15-societe/283533-premier-cas-autochtone-de-rougeole.html


The Indian Ocean Health Agency (L'Agence de Sante Ocean Indien) has
reported that this week, an autochthonous case of measles has been
confirmed. The case is a 26-year-old unvaccinated woman. At present,
her condition is not a cause for concern.

The island Health Service [L'Agence de Sante Ocean Indien] has stated
that vaccination is the only protection against measles virus
infection. Two injections are essential to provide compete immunity.
The vaccine recommended is the triple MMR vaccine, providing
protection against mumps, measles and rubella.

L'Agence de Sante Ocean Indien strongly recommends that both the
general population and particularly those likely to travel abroad
should verify their vaccination status to ensure that they have
received both doses of the MMR vaccine. The measles outbreak in
metropolitan France and elsewhere continues unabated and affects
adults and young people as well as children and babies. Measles
infection is often erroneously considered to be benign, whereas
serious consequences can ensue. Those who have previously contracted
measles and have recovered remain protected. For the rest of the
population, vaccination remains the best option.

Vaccination can be carried out by general practitioners and at
pediatric clinics without charge. Since October 2010, health assurance
polices will cover the cost of 2 doses of MMR vaccine for children up
to the age of 17, and 65 percent of the cost for others.

--
Communicated by:
HealthMap alerts via ProMED-mail
