[9] USA (California)
Date: Fri 13 May 2011
Source: The Orange County Register [edited]
http://www.ocregister.com/articles/measles-300494-children-health.html


Measles is on the rise in California, with one case reported in
Orange County, state health officials said Friday [13 May 2011]. The
extremely contagious virus is spreading through travel to developing
nations or Europe, where some parents choose not to vaccinate.

Among California's 13 cases, 7 have been reported since April 2011,
the Department of Public Health announced. In Orange County, an
unidentified child contracted measles while traveling overseas, said
Health Care Agency spokeswoman Tricia Landquist. "California, like the
rest of the nation and, indeed, the world, is experiencing an increase
in measles cases that is entirely preventable with immunization," said
Dr. Gilberto Chavez, Deputy Director for Infectious Diseases, in a
statement. "Anyone who will be traveling or is expecting contact with
recent international travelers should confirm that their vaccinations
are up-to-date."

Measles outbreaks are underway in India, the Philippines and Europe,
including deaths in France. In Europe, the illnesses are blamed on
reduced vaccination rates because of the fear of children developing
autism. Last year [2010], a prominent British medical journal
retracted a study that had connected the measles, mumps and rubella
vaccine to autism. Among every 1000 children who become ill with
measles, one or 2 will die from the disease, according to the Centers
for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC).

The CDC recommends the following: 2 doses of vaccine for children,
the 1st at 12 to 15 months and the 2nd dose before entering school at
4 to 6. Before international travel, infants 6 to 11 months old should
have at least one dose. Children 12 months of age or older should have
2 doses separated by at least 28 days. Adults should review their
vaccination records to determine if they need to be vaccinated.

The [Orange] county's Health Care Agency provides free MMR
immunizations for eligible children.

[Byline: Courtney Perkes]

