[10] USA (Florida)
Date: Fri 13 May 2011
Source: Orlando Sentinel [edited]
http://www.orlandosentinel.com/health/os-orlando-measles-20110513,0,585164.story


An Orange County preschooler has been diagnosed with measles, the 1st
case of a local resident getting the disease in 17 years, health
officials say. The preschooler attended a function at a private school
and also visited a doctor's office and a hospital recently. Orange
County Health Department staffers notified officials at all 3
locations, instructing those who have not been vaccinated against
measles to stay home until 20 May 2011 when the incubation period
ends.

The child is recovering and is at home, said Dain Weister, Orange
County Health Department spokesman. "We've not had a problem for many
years," said Dain Weister. "There have been some outbreaks across the
country; specifically Europe is having a problem right now and
problems from travel, but we haven't had a local case."

The medical community also has been notified to be on the watch for
rash-like illnesses. Residents who received routine measles
vaccination as children will have immunity and in most cases will be
protected.

The new case is not related to the 3 measles cases in tourists that
were reported in early April [2011]. In those cases, 3 tourists from
Texas, Michigan and Minnesota who traveled to Orlando were diagnosed
with measles. Health authorities were unsure whether the travelers
caught the disease from an Orlando resident or whether one tourist
spread it to another. The latest case is not related, Weister said,
because so much time has elapsed between those incidences and this
one.

Health officials remind parents that the best way to protect their
children is to make sure they are immunized against measles by the
combination MMR (measles, mumps and rubella) vaccine. Children should
receive 2 doses, the 1st at 12 to 15 months of age, and the 2nd at 4
to 6 years of age.

Symptoms of measles generally begin about one to 2 weeks after a
person is infected, and include a blotchy rash, fever, cough, runny
nose and conjunctivitis as well as achy, run-down feelings and tiny
white spots with bluish-white centers inside the mouth. Measles is
spread through the air by infectious droplets and is highly
contagious. It can be transmitted from 4 days before the rash becomes
visible to 4 days after the rash appears. For information about
measles and vaccination information, go to
http://www.cdc.gov/measles/index.html or
http://orchd.com/personalHealth/immunizations/index.asp.

[Byline: Linda Shrieves]

